          "summary": "XML is a standardized markup language that defines a set of rules for encoding hierarchically structured documents in a human-readable text-based format. XML is in widespread use, with documents ranging from very short and simple (such as SOAP queries) to multi-gigabyte documents (OpenStreetMap) with complicated data relationships ( COLLADA ). In order to process XML documents, users typically need a special library: an XML parser, which converts the document from text to internal representation. XML is a compromise between parsing performance, human readability and parsing-code complexity–therefore a fast XML parser can make the choice of XML as an underlying format for application data model more preferable. This chapter describes various performance tricks that allowed the author to write a very high-performing parser in C++: pugixml . While the techniques were used for an XML parser, most of them can be applied to parsers of other formats or even unrelated software (e.g., memory management algorithms are widely applicable beyond parsers).",
