      "sessionKind": "chapter",
      "summary": "A vast star empire encompasses a hundred worlds, stretching a thousand parsecs across space. Unlike some other areas of the galaxy, few warriors live here; this is an intellectual people, with a rich cultural and academic tradition. Their magnificent planets, built turn by turn around great universities of science and technology, are a beacon of light to all in this age of peace and prosperity. Starships arrive from the vast reaches of the quadrant and beyond, bearing the foremost researchers from far and wide. They come to contribute their skills to the most ambitious project ever attempted by sentient beings: the development of a decentralized computer network to connect the entire galaxy, with all its various languages, cultures, and systems of law. Thousand Parsec is more than a video game: it is a framework, with a complete toolkit for building multiplayer, turn-based space empire strategy games. Its generic game protocol allows diverse implementations of client, server, and AI software, as well as a vast array of possible games. Though its size has made planning and execution challenging, forcing contributors to walk a thin line between excessively vertical and excessively horizontal development, it also makes it a rather interesting specimen when discussing the architecture of open source applications.",
